# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bailey-willis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:bailey-willis/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:bailey-willis/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:bailey-willis/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:bailey-willis/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:bailey-willis/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:bailey-willis/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:bailey-willis/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The **American Association of Petroleum Geologists** (**AAPG**) is one of the world's largest professional geological societies with about 17,000 members across 129 countries.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Over the years, the activities of the AAPG have broadened so that they bring together not just geology but also geophysics, geochemistry, engineering, and innovative analytics to enable the more efficient and environmentally-friendly approaches to the development of all earth-based energy sources.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] New transformative technologies, such as the ability to better characterize reservoirs through imaging and the integration of multiple data sources, are coupled with concerns about the environment.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Members and affiliated societies are very much involved in preserving the quality of groundwater, dealing responsibly with produced water, and understanding the mechanisms of induced seismicity.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In addition to subsurface investigations, the society supports mapping of the surface and the use of new technologies (UAVs, drones, big data analytics), with the goals of advancing the science and understanding of geological processes.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG publishes the *AAPG Explorer* magazine and *AAPG Bulletin* scientific journal, and co-publishes a scientific journal with the Society of Exploration Geophysicists called *Interpretation*.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The organization holds an annual meeting including a technical conference and exhibition, sponsors other conferences and continuing education for members around the world such as ongoing Geosciences Technology Workshops, and provides various other services to its members.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The organization also includes divisions focused on particular aspects of the profession.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] These include the Division of Environmental Geosciences, Division of Professional Affairs, and the Energy and Minerals Division.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The association membership has included Harrison "Jack" Schmitt, a U.S. astronaut who walked on the Moon.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] At its annual conventions and international conferences AAPG recognizes the distinguished contributions in the field of petroleum geosciences with various awards, including the Sidney Powers Memorial Award, Michel T.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Halbouty Outstanding Leadership Award, Grover E.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Murray Memorial Distinguished Educator Award, Wallace Pratt Memorial Award, and Ziad Rafiq Beydoun Memorial Award.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG IBA award is given immediately following the IBA competition that is held at that year's annual convention.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG promotes student involvement in the profession by holding an annual Imperial Barrel Award competition where geoscience graduate students are encouraged to explore a career in the energy industry.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In this global competition, university teams analyze a dataset (geology, geophysics, land, production infrastructure, and other relevant materials) and deliver their results in a 25-minute presentation.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The students' presentations are judged by industry experts, providing the students a real-world, career-development experience.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] IBA offers students and their faculty advisor a chance to win accolades for themselves and cash prizes for their schools, and winning teams travel free to the annual AAPG convention to network with both future colleagues and future employers.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The Correlation of Stratigraphic Units of North America (COSUNA) was a project of the AAPG which resulted in the publication of sixteen correlation charts depicting modern concepts of the stratigraphy of North America.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG has supported the investigation of the earth, and over the years, ideas about how oil is formed have changed.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In the 1960s, the AAPG supported the then-revolutionary idea of plate tectonics (vs. isostasy), and looked at plate tectonics as a key to the evolution of basins, and thus the formation of oil and gas.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] An example is Tanya Atwater's work on plate tectonics.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] As a whole, women geoscientists have played an important role in the AAPG's 100-year history as scientists and leaders.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Since that time, the AAPG has worked closely with scientific organizations such as the USGS to apply new scientific breakthroughs to the generation, migration, and entrapment of oil and gas.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The results have brought new understanding of ultra-deepwater reservoirs (such as off the coast of Brazil).
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG has supported geomechanics in order to be able to predict pore pressure and avoid drilling hazards.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG has also been supportive of investigations having to do with the impact of policies of disposing of produced water by injecting it into deep formations.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Workshops and forums have been held since 2009 (Geosciences Technology Workshops) to analyze the problems and to discuss solutions.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] They have been held throughout the world, and are documented through the presentations.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The presentations from the workshops have been made available for free via the AAPG's open access online journal, Search and Discovery.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In 2006, the AAPG was criticized for selecting author Michael Crichton for their Journalism Award for *Jurassic Park* and "for his recent science-based thriller *State of Fear*", in which Crichton exposed his rejection of scientific evidence for anthropogenic global warming.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Schrag, a geochemist who directs the Harvard University Center for the Environment, called the award "a total embarrassment" that he said "reflects the politics of the oil industry and a lack of professionalism" on the association's part.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The criticism drew attention to the AAPG's 1999 position statement formally rejecting the likelihood of human influence on recent climate.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Acknowledging that the association's previous policy statement on Climate Change was "not supported by a significant number of our members and prospective members", AAPG's formal stance was reviewed and changed in July 2007.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The new statement formally accepts human activity as at least one contributor to carbon dioxide increase, but does not confirm its link to climate change, saying its members are "divided on the degree of influence that anthropogenic CO2 has" on climate.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG also withdrew its earlier criticism of other scientific organizations and research stating, "Certain climate simulation models predict that the warming trend will continue, as reported through NAS, AGU, AAAS, and AMS.
[src:bailey-willis/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG respects these scientific opinions but wants to add that the current climate warming projections could fall within well-documented natural variations in past climate and observed temperature data.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:bailey-willis/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] Bailey Willis was born March 31, 1857, the son of poet and publisher Nathaniel Parker Willis and Cornelia Grinnell Willis.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] His father died when he was only ten years old.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] At the age of thirteen he was taken to England and Germany for four years of schooling, and thus acquired fluency in German at a time when many scientific texts were only available in that language.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] He entered Columbia University and in five years completed his studies with the degrees of mechanical (1878) and civil (1879) engineer.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] Willis married his cousin, Altona Grinnell, in 1882, but she died in 1896.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] The couple had two children, Marion, who died in infancy, and Hope, later Mrs.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] In 1898 he married Margaret Baker, daughter of Dr.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] Frank Baker of Georgetown University, who was also superintendent of the National Zoo in Washington, D.C.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] The children of his second marriage are Cornelius G.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] The family lived for many years on the Stanford University campus.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] After receiving degrees in mining engineering and civil engineering, Willis worked from 1881 to 1884 as a survey geologist for Northern Pacific Railroad looking for sources of coal.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] Called the "boy boss" by work crews during his work looking for coal, he began studying the geology of Mount Rainier, the Cascade Range, and the Rocky Mountains.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] From 1884 to 1915, he worked for the USGS, being named director of the Appalachian division in 1889.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] In 1893 he published "The Mechanics of Appalachian Structure" in the *Report of the United States Geological Survey*.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] From 1895 to 1902 he lectured on geology at Johns Hopkins University.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] In 1900 he was appointed head of the Division of Areal Geology of the USGS.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] In 1903 he received a grant of $12,000 from the newly established Carnegie Institution of Washington to lead an expedition to northern China, an experience which was later described in his book *Friendly China*.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1905.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] From 1910 until 1914 he consulted for the government of Argentina an experience later recorded in his book *A Yanqui in Patagonia*.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] Willis also called for comprehensive state intervention in the enforcement of the national park at Lake Nahuel Huapí.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] He was commissioned by the Director General de Agricultura, Dr.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] Julio López Mañán, to prepare a study on the Nahuel Huapi National Park.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] This study first appeared in 1913 in a brochure published by the Dirección de Agricultura y Defensa Agrícola and was later reprinted in his book *El Norte de la Patagonia* under the title "Parque Nacional del Sud".
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] Willis had probably discussed these ideas intensively with Moreno and also with Emilio Frey.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] When he returned to the United States in 1915 he was named Head of the Stanford University Geology Department.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] He led a vigorous public campaign in the 1920s to raise awareness of earthquake hazards and safe building practices.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] It is claimed that many of California's early building codes were inspired by experiments performed by Willis on an "earthquake table" at Stanford University.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] Willis, concerned about the dangers of earthquakes convinced engineers to dig the foundation of the southern tower of the Golden Gate Bridge deeper.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] After finishing his work with the USGS, he was appointed as a professor and chairman of the geology department at Stanford University, where he served until 1922.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] In 1920, he was elected to the National Academy of the Sciences.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] He was president of the Seismological Society of America from 1921 to 1926, during which time he published his *Geologic Structures*.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1928.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] On July 11, 1927, while in Cairo, Egypt, he heard that a destructive earthquake struck the Holy Land.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] The day after, he took a private flight from Cairo to Palestine, made observations of the impacted sites, and stayed there for several days to further investigate.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] A year later, he published his findings in the Bulitin of Seismological Society of America.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] In 1928, he published "Continental Drift" in the *SP 2: Theory of Continental Drift*, by the American Association of Petroleum Geologists, where he rejects the theory.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] From 1921 to 1927 he was President of the Seismological Society.
[src:bailey-willis/bailey-willis] The Willis Wall on the north face of Mount Rainier is named for him, and *Choconsaurus baileywillisi* is also named for him.
